NPCs.

NPCs are the living entities that populate a map. Animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, zombies, and specials all share one engine: each one walks the map, picks targets, attacks, takes damage, and dies under a unified system driven entirely by data.
Every numerical knob that controls how a creature behaves lives in a plain text info.sif file beside its sound folder, so authoring a new creature is mostly a matter of dropping audio in the right folder and writing a small text file next to it.

Every NPC belongs to one of seven categories: animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, zombies, or specials.
The category determines the sound pool used for its audio, and it doubles as a target tag that other NPCs can attack or ignore.

Humans are special in one respect: they auto roll a random weapon category and subtype on spawn, parse that weapon's info.sif, and fire it through the same weapon class the player uses. A human's bullet inherits the weapon's damage, range, bullet speed, fire cadence, ammo, stun mode, launch type, scadder zone, refchance, and refchance cushion, so a sniper rifle outranges a pistol, a rocket launcher actually launches rockets in human hands, a scadder weapon splash-damages targets near the impact, and a reflective weapon's failed reflection halves continuing damage if the weapon was authored with refchance=N:true. When a non melee human runs out of loaded ammo, the engine triggers the weapon's reload clip on the human's clock and resumes firing once the reload finishes, exactly like the player does.
The stun rider applies symmetrically: a human armed with a tazer rifle freezes the player on hit just like the player would freeze a wolf with the same weapon, gated on the damage actually going through (a melee block or full shield absorption ducks the stun the same way it ducks the hurt clip). The push rider works the same way: a human carrying a weapon with push x, push y, or push z set shoves the player on hit exactly like the player would shove a wolf with the same weapon, and an npc that lands a push-equipped hit on another npc shoves it just the same, so a wind gun authored for the player turns every human carrying it into a wind gunner without any extra wiring.

Specials is a catch all bucket for creatures that don't cleanly fit any of the other categories. It behaves identically to animals, robots, and zombies, with no human only weapon logic, so anything you'd normally author as an animal, robot, or zombie can live under specials instead when its theme doesn't match those names.
Bosses is a thematic folder for big bad creatures. It behaves like specials, animals, robots, and zombies under the hood, so the slot is purely for organizing major encounters away from the everyday roster without forcing them to share a folder with the wildlife.

Helpers is the friendly category. A helper inverts the targets field as a protected list and gains two helpers only overlays: it picks up dropped items on contact when the player is in its protected list, and it drifts back toward the player when no enemy is in sight and the player is in its protected list. Helpers also play a remove clip from their own folder when the map tears down, so a follower can have its own farewell sound. Everything else, terrain, chase mode, hit and run, summons, weapons, behaves identically to the other categories, so a helper is mechanically a normal npc with three extra behaviors.

Each NPC has three behavior states baked in at runtime.

The normal state is the default.
The wounded state kicks in when the creature drops below a configured health threshold and the threat is still in wounded sight range, and in this state the creature flips its movement and walks away from the threat instead of toward it.

The healing state takes over when the creature is below the threshold but no threat is in wounded sight, and it stops moving, drops its target, and ticks its own health back up over time.

Every numeric stat can be tuned per state, so a creature can be more aggressive while wounded, weaker while healing, or anything in between.

Sound packs and info.sif files.

NPC stats live in info.sif files inside the sound pack.
The engine looks for these files in two places: the current map's local pack at data/builder/maps/decompiled/<map>/assets/builder/kombat/npc/<category>/<subtype>/data/info.sif, and the global default pack at sounds/default/builder/kombat/npc/<category>/<subtype>/data/info.sif.

The map local copy wins if both exist, so a map can override a global creature's stats without affecting any other map.

Each creature has its own info.sif at builder/kombat/npc/<category>/<subtype>/data/info.sif. The file is self contained: every stat the creature uses is written explicitly, and anything left out falls through to the engine defaults the game uses for creatures.

The info.sif file does not list any sounds. The engine learns what audio a creature has by scanning the creature's general/ subfolder, matching whatever clips it finds against the names it expects (hurt, death, spawn, taunt, step, fall, heal, and so on). Drop a clip in general/ and the creature plays it; remove it and the creature goes silent for that event. There is nothing to wire up by hand because the folder layout is the audio configuration.

Field reference.

Every field in info.sif uses the form key=value, one per line.

Numeric fields can take a single number for a constant, a colon delimited triple for state specific values, or a comma range for a randomized roll.
The triple format is normal:wounded:healing for most numeric fields, where leaving out the second or third part falls back to the first.

A few fields override this convention with their own slot meanings.

Health uses a:b:c where a is max health, b is the wounded threshold, and c is the heal amount per tick.
Chase mode uses trigger:wander, with each slot a string from a fixed enum.

Chase time uses calm:random:pause, with each slot a per-purpose timer rather than a per-state value.
Teleport time uses normal:wounded:healing like most fields, but each slot accepts the literal never to disable that state, since 0 also disables.

The comma format is min,max for a fresh random roll on each use.
Fields can mix the two: 5000,15000:1000,5000:5000,15000 gives a different range per state.

Most numeric fields also accept the tokens maxx, maxy, maxz, minx, miny, and minz.
These resolve to the map's bounds at parse time, which lets a creature cover the entire map with x sight range=maxx without baking a hard coded number into a globally shared file. The z tokens are only meaningful on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps z fields are ignored regardless of what they hold.

x attack range (triple int): How many tiles along the x axis the creature has to be within of its target before it can attack. Zero means the target must share the same x as the creature.
y attack range (triple int): How many tiles along the y axis the creature has to be within of its target before it can attack.
z attack range (triple int): How many tiles along the z axis (height) the creature has to be within of its target before it can attack. Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the z gate is bypassed and the field is effectively ignored.

For unarmed creatures (animals, robots, zombies, specials, helpers without weapons, and humans whose weapon roll did not pick anything) att range is the actual contact damage range, since the engine applies damage directly without spawning a bullet. Att range zero on these is fine and means a same tile bite, claw, or punch.
For armed humans the picture splits in two depending on the weapon's melee field. A human carrying a melee weapon (melee=true in the weapon's info.sif) does direct contact damage the same way unarmed creatures do, with no bullet spawned, the swing landing the moment the human pulls the trigger, and att range serving as the actual hit range. A human carrying a ranged weapon (melee=false) spawns a real bullet from the weapon. Att range gates when the human pulls the trigger, while the weapon's own x range, y range, and z range fields govern how far the spawned bullet actually travels before despawning.

The three distances do not have to match: a stand off shotgun feel can use a short att range with a long weapon range, and a sniper rifle feel can use a long att range with an even longer weapon range, but att range should never exceed weapon range or the human will trigger from far enough away that the bullet despawns before reaching you. Att range zero on an armed human still works thanks to the bullet's first tick hit check at its spawn position, so a same tile point blank fire connects without the bullet needing to travel.
Two melee specific fields stay player only when a human carries the weapon. The swing speed wind-up is always zero on npc swings — the strike is instant the moment the human pulls the trigger regardless of what the weapon's swing speed value says. Melee scadder is also player only — a human swinging a scadder=R melee weapon still only hits the player and never cleaves into other npcs nearby, because npc melee uses a direct contact hit instead of the player's scatter-aware melee pipeline.

Bullet scadder, on the other hand, does work for ranged weapons in human hands. When an armed human fires a scadder ranged weapon, the spawned bullet carries the weapon's scadder radius and count and triggers the same splash on impact that a player-fired bullet does — so a human armed with a rocket launcher authored with scadder=3:5 splashes nearby targets exactly the way it would in player hands.

Humans are also orthogonal to the player's per-type ammo and damage system. The player's character-wide reserve_<type> pools and damage_<type> bonuses (set in kombat.sif and bought through the shop) only apply to weapons the player carries — a human armed with the same battery rifle does not draw from your battery reserve and does not benefit from your battery damage upgrade. NPC weapons fall back to the legacy per-weapon ammo field (defaulting to 100) for their reload pool and use only their own attack stat for damage, so npc combat is fully independent of the player's economy. This is intentional: it means fighting battery-armed humans never drains your battery ammo even when you're not the one shooting, and it keeps the per-type system a player-side build choice rather than a shared resource pool with every npc on the map.

x sight range (triple int): How far along the x axis the creature can see a target. The creature only pursues a target inside this range under sight based chase modes. Setting this to maxx makes the creature aware of targets anywhere on the map's x axis.
y sight range (triple int): The y axis equivalent of x sight range.
z sight range (triple int): The z axis (height) equivalent. Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored.

health (special triple): The creature's hit points. Written as a:b:c where a is the maximum starting health, b is the wounded threshold the creature drops below to enter wounded mode, and c is the amount of health restored on each tick of healing. Writing a single number leaves wounded and healing disabled. The wounded threshold is the gateway: leaving b at zero means the creature never enters wounded or healing mode no matter what other state specific values are set.
rest heal time (single int): Milliseconds between heal ticks while the creature is in healing mode (below the wounded threshold and with no target in wounded sight). Accepts a comma range like 4000,8000 for a fresh roll on parse. Only fires while the third value of health is set.

ambient heal time (single int): Milliseconds between heal ticks while ambient heal is on. Runs on its own clock independent of rest heal time, so a creature can slowly trickle health back during a fight and then rest faster while hiding, or vice versa. Accepts a comma range. Only fires while ambient heal is true and the third value of health is set.
ambient heal (bool): When true, the ambient heal time clock starts ticking and the creature regenerates health no matter what state it is in, including while attacking. When false, the ambient clock is ignored and only the rest heal time clock can heal the creature. Either way the creature is clamped to its max health, so this never raises the cap.

lives (triple int): How many lives the creature has. Each life refills health on death until the last one runs out.

attack (triple int): The base damage the creature deals on a successful attack. Modified at runtime by level.
defense (triple int): Damage reduction applied to incoming hits. The actual reduction is defense times three, so a defense of ten removes thirty raw damage.

fire speed (triple int): Milliseconds between attack swings. Lower values mean a faster attacker.
move speed (triple int): Milliseconds between movement ticks. Lower values mean a faster mover.

level (triple double): A multiplier on attack damage and xp drop. Level one is neutral.
xp (triple double): The xp value the creature drops when killed, multiplied by level and the player's xpmod.

attacking (bool): Whether the creature can fire at all. Setting this to false makes a creature that walks but never swings.

weapon type (string): For humans only, which weapon category the human is allowed to roll at spawn. Accepts the literal word random to keep the original behavior of picking any category on the map (this is the default and matches every legacy human npc file out there), or any specific category folder name under main/equipments/weapons to pin the roll to that category. The npc builder's add and edit forms expose this as a list selector populated from the on-disk categories so authors don't have to remember exact spelling. Defaults to random.
weapon type2 (string): The matching subtype pin. Accepts random (the default, picks any subtype inside the chosen category), or any specific weapon folder name to force that exact weapon. Combined with weapon type you get four authoring patterns: random/random for the original fully-random roll, named/random for a category-locked roll (e.g. weapon type=melee with weapon type2=random for a melee-only human), random/named for a subtype-locked roll where the engine scans every category to find which one owns the named subtype (weapon type=random with weapon type2=long_rope for a long-rope wielder regardless of which folder long_rope happens to live in), and named/named for an exact fixed weapon (weapon type=melee with weapon type2=long_rope). A typo or a folder that no longer exists silently falls back to a fully random roll so a deleted weapon never leaves the human unarmed.

move x (bool): Whether the creature is allowed to move along the x axis.
move y (bool): Whether the creature is allowed to move along the y axis.
move z (bool): Whether the creature is allowed to move along the z axis (height). Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored.

drop item (bool): Whether the creature has a chance to drop a healing or stamina item on death.

chase mode (string pair): Two parts joined with a colon as trigger:wander. The trigger part decides when the creature pursues and accepts sight, always, provoke, random, or never. Sight pursues whenever a valid target is in sight range. Always pursues regardless of sight. Provoke only pursues after the creature has been hit, and calms down after losing sight for chase time's first slot. Note that this is the explicit trigger value, separate from the universal provoke on hit override described below, which applies on top of every trigger except never. Random flips between pursuing and not pursuing on a clock controlled by chase time's second slot. Never refuses to chase but still defends in attack range. The wander part decides what the creature does while not pursuing and accepts none, roam, or patrol. None stands still. Roam picks random destinations within move x and move y bounds and pauses between them for chase time's third slot. Patrol walks the corners of its move bounds in a fixed loop.
Provoke on hit. Any creature that takes damage flips to a provoked state and starts chasing whatever attacked it, regardless of which chase trigger it was authored with. A creature with chase mode=sight that has not yet seen you will still charge after you put a bullet in it, then calm down again after losing sight for chase time's calm slot. The one exception is chase mode=never, which is the only trigger that opts out of this universal provoke override. A never creature stays put under fire, only swinging back if you walk into its attack range.

chase time (triple range): Three timer slots joined with colons as calm:random:pause, all in milliseconds. Each slot supports comma ranges for a fresh random roll. Calm controls how long a provoked creature stays angry after losing sight. Random controls how long each phase of the random trigger lasts before flipping. Pause controls how long a roaming creature stops between destinations. Slots not relevant to the chosen chase mode are ignored.
teleport time (triple range): Three timer slots joined with colons as normal:wounded:healing, all in milliseconds. Each slot supports comma ranges for a fresh random roll on each tick, like 5000,15000 for a teleport every five to fifteen seconds. Each slot also accepts the literal never to disable teleporting in that state, so teleport time=5000:never:never makes the creature teleport on the normal clock but never while wounded or healing. The destination uses the creature's patrol x range, patrol y range, and patrol z range gated by tel x, tel y, and tel z, the creature's *tel* clip plays at the new tile, and the loop sound follows along.

tel x (bool): Whether a teleport tick is allowed to randomize the creature's x coordinate.
tel y (bool): Whether a teleport tick is allowed to randomize the creature's y coordinate.
tel z (bool): Whether a teleport tick is allowed to randomize the creature's z coordinate (height). Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored.

With every tel bool false the teleport feature is off entirely, so the time field is ignored.

use steps (string): Which step sound the creature plays as it walks. Accepts auto, own, player, or never. Auto tries the creature's own step clip first and falls back to the surface's step clip when the creature has none, so a creature with its own footsteps always sounds like itself and only borrows the surface clip when nothing better is available. Own always plays the creature's own folder step clip regardless of surface, so a robot always sounds metal even on grass. Player plays only the surface's step clip and stays silent on tiles missing one, matching exactly what the player hears walking that same tile. Never silences footsteps entirely, useful for ghosts, floating creatures, or anything that should not betray its position.
use falls (string): Which fall sound the creature's body plays when it dies and hits the ground. Accepts auto, own, player, or never with the same meaning as use steps. Auto tries the creature's own fall clip first and falls back to the surface fall clip if the creature has none. Own forces the creature's own fall clip, player forces the surface fall clip, and never plays nothing on death.

terrain (string list): Which surface tiles the creature is allowed to step onto, with optional per tile territorial charge speeds. Accepts the literal any to allow every tile, or a comma list of tile names like grass,dirt,wood that the creature's destination tile must contain to be a valid step. Matching is substring based, so terrain=grass accepts grass, grass1, hardgrass, and any other tile whose name contains grass. When the creature tries to walk onto a tile that does not match, the step is silently skipped and the creature keeps trying other directions on the next tick, so a wolf with terrain=grass,dirt walking across a grass field with a strip of water in the way paces the shoreline instead of wading in. If the creature is already standing on a forbidden tile, for example because it was placed there by the author or teleported onto it, the restriction is temporarily bypassed so it can walk in any direction until it lands on a valid tile, after which the rule kicks back in.
Each tile name can be suffixed with a colon and a charge cadence to make that tile a defended territory, written as terrain=grass:250 or terrain=grass:250,dirt:500,water,sand. While the player stands on any defended tile of the creature, the creature is forced into the provoked state and moves at the suffixed speed in milliseconds per step instead of its normal move speed, then drops back to normal once the player steps off and the chase time calm window expires. Tiles without a colon or with a colon zero like grass:0 are walkable but not defended, so the creature ignores the player while it stands there. flee speed during a hit and run retreat still wins over the territorial speed, and the territorial speed wins over provoke speed, so a creature with terrain, provoke speed, and flee speed all set has four distinct cadences for normal travel, defending its turf, charging after being hit elsewhere, and fleeing.

hit and run (bool): When true, the creature flees for flee time milliseconds the moment its attack lands, then resumes its normal chase logic and lines up the next swing. While fleeing it can't attack and runs away from its target the same way the wounded state does, regardless of the creature's actual health, so a hit and run skirmisher dashes in for one swing, retreats for the configured window, dashes back in for the next swing, and so on. Useful for ranged enemies that should never sit still next to the player and for scout type npcs that pepper you with chip damage between escapes.

flee time (single int): Milliseconds the creature retreats after each successful attack while hit and run is on. Accepts a comma range like 1500,3000 for a fresh roll on parse. Setting flee time to zero disables the retreat even if hit and run is true.
flee speed (single int): Milliseconds between movement ticks while the creature is fleeing. Accepts a comma range. Lower values mean a faster retreat. Leaving flee speed at zero falls back to the creature's normal move speed, so the npc retreats at the same pace it approaches. Setting flee speed lower than move speed makes a hit and run skirmisher actually outrun you between swings, which is what makes the pattern feel threatening rather than easy.

chase terrains (bool): When true, the terrain restriction is dropped any time the creature is provoked or fleeing, so the creature stays on its habitat tiles while peaceful but breaks cover the moment it has a reason to chase. Useful for territorial predators that should hunt anyone who shoots them from outside their habitat instead of pacing the boundary unable to retaliate. Leaves the false default unchanged for everything else, so an existing creature stays habitat bound in every state until you flip this on.

provoke speed (single int): Milliseconds between movement ticks while the creature is in the provoked state. Accepts a comma range. Lower values mean a faster charge. Leaving provoke speed at zero falls back to the creature's normal move speed, so a provoked npc charges at the same pace it normally moves. Applies any time the creature is provoked, whether that came from chase mode=provoke or from being hit while in any other chase mode, and is overridden by flee speed during the hit and run flee window so the three cadences stay distinct.

launching (bool): When true, the creature periodically summons another npc on the launch time clock. The summoned creature is forced to have its own launching off so chains cannot snowball. Pauses while the launcher is in healing mode so the creature is not doing two things at once.
launch path (string): Which info file the summoned creature reads its stats from, mirroring the path field on a regular spawn line. Accepts any, global, or map. Any uses the map's own copy if one exists and falls back to the shared sound pack otherwise. Global pins the summon to the shared sound pack version. Map pins it to the map's own copy and refuses the global fallback.

launch category (string): Which folder the summoned creature is read from. Accepts animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, zombies, or specials. Anything else makes the launch tick a no op. Projectiles are intentionally not supported here since this is the npc system, not the kombat system.
launch subtype (string): Which specific creature to summon under the chosen launch category. Accepts a single name like wolf to always summon the same one, a comma list like wolf,bear,tiger to pick one at random per launch from a curated set, or the literal random to pick any folder under the launch category. Any name can be suffixed with a colon and a scale level to override the launcher's level when the minion is spawned, so wolf:0 spawns wolf with the scale level zero (using its info.sif stats verbatim) and bear:5 spawns bear at scale level five. Mixing scales in a curated list works too, like wolf:0,bear:2,tiger to give wolf and bear hand picked levels while tiger inherits the launcher's level. Random can also take a scale, written as random:0 or random:3.

launch time (single int): Milliseconds between launch ticks. Accepts a comma range like 8000,15000 for a fresh roll on parse. Runs on its own clock independent of the attack and movement clocks, regardless of state, so a launching creature keeps summoning while attacking, while wounded, and while healing.

patrol x range (range): Minimum and maximum x tiles the creature will roam, patrol, or teleport into, written as min,max. Each value accepts the tokens minx and maxx as well as a literal number, so patrol x range=15,30 confines a guard to a thirty tile post on the x axis and patrol x range=minx,maxx restores the full map sweep. Writing patrol x range=terrain by itself auto fits the patrol bounds to the contiguous habitat the creature spawns on, scanning along the x axis from the spawn tile until the next tile fails the terrain check, so a bear with terrain=grass:150 and patrol x range=terrain confines its roaming to whatever grass patch it spawned on no matter where on the map it is placed. Pursuit is left unbounded, so a guard can still chase the player past their post and walk back when calm.
patrol y range (range): The y axis equivalent of patrol x range, with miny and maxy as the supported tokens, and the same terrain auto fit token that scans along the y axis from the spawn tile.
patrol z range (range): The z axis (height) equivalent of patrol x range, with minz and maxz as the supported tokens. Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored.

All three ranges default to the full map when absent. The roam destination picker, patrol corner picker, and teleport destination picker all read from these fields, so a single patrol box keeps a creature anchored across all three movement modes.

targets (csv list): What the creature attacks. The default is player, matching the original behavior. Other accepted values are animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, zombies, specials, the shorthand all for everything, and the special value none for a fully passive creature that walks around without attacking anything. Multiple values can be combined with commas, like player,zombies for a creature that hunts you and zombies but ignores everyone else.
A creature with targets=none is also invulnerable. Bullets pass through them without dealing damage or being consumed, so a pacifist villager cannot be killed by player or npc fire, only despawned with the map.

For the helpers category the targets field reads inversely as a protected list. A helper attacks every entity that is not in its targets list and never attacks anything that is.

The default for a fresh helper info file is targets=player,helpers, which means do not attack the player or other helpers and do attack every other category, giving you a standard ally that hunts your enemies and won't friendly fire other allies. targets=animals on a helper makes a guardian that defends livestock and attacks anything threatening them including the player, targets=all is a pacifist sanctuary helper that protects everyone and attacks no one, and targets=none is a feral helper that protects no one and attacks everyone including you.
Helpers also pick up dropped items on contact, but only when the player is in the protected list, so a feral or wildlife guardian helper will never gather items for you. When no enemy is in sight and the player is in the protected list a helper drifts back toward the player instead of roaming, taking precedence over the chase mode wander field.

NPC builder.

Opening the NPC entry from the builder menu brings up a five button chooser that covers every authoring action: add, edit, remove, spawn, and view.
The same form reopens after each action so you can chain operations without bouncing back to the map.

Add. Picks a path, category, and subtype from three lists, then opens a flat form with every parsed info.sif field as its own input plus checkboxes for the booleans.
The path list chooses whether the file is written to the global default pack or to the current map's local pack.

The category and subtype lists are populated from the actual folders on disk under the chosen path.
Every field is required on save, with no defaults, so the saved file always has a complete entry for every key.

If an info.sif already exists for the chosen NPC the form prompts to overwrite before writing.

Edit. Same three list selection as Add, but the subtype list filters to only show creatures that already have an info.sif.
Selecting one opens the same flat form prefilled with the existing values.

Saving silently overwrites the file with no prompt because editing always intends to replace what's there.

Remove. Picks a path and a category, then offers a multi select list of configured subtypes.
Toggling subtypes with space adds them to the deletion set, and pressing remove brings up a confirmation prompt with the count of files about to be deleted.

Only the info.sif files are removed; the audio folders themselves are left untouched.

Spawn. Routes to the existing direct spawn flow, which is the same form that used to open before the chooser was added.
Asks for x, y, scale level, a path, and a category and subtype, then writes the spawn line into the map's info.sif and immediately spawns the creature.

The path list here has three options: any, global, and map. Any merges both pools into the subtype list and lets the spawned creature use the map local copy when present and the global one otherwise. Global filters the subtype list to only what's in the global pack and pins the spawn to read from there. Map filters to only what's in the map's local pack and pins the spawn to read from there. The chosen path is stored on the spawn line so each creature remembers which source to use.
Important: path only controls which info.sif file the creature reads its stats from. It does not redirect where sounds come from. Sound lookup always runs its own search, checking the compiled map pack first, then the map's local assets folder, then the shared sound pack, no matter what path the spawn line uses. So a creature pinned to global with path=global still plays map local sounds if you've placed any in the map's assets folder, and a creature pinned to map with path=map still falls back to the shared sound pack for any clips the map doesn't ship its own copy of. The same rule applies to launch path on launching creatures.

View. Picks a path, category, and subtype like the others, with the subtype list filtered to configured creatures.
Below the lists is a read only multiline contents box that shows the raw info.sif text for the focused subtype.

Arrowing through the subtype list updates the contents box in real time so you can scan multiple files without reopening the form.

Spawn line format.

When the Spawn button writes a creature into a map, it appends a line to the map's info.sif at data/builder/maps/decompiled/<map>/info.sif in the form npc x y scale path category subtype on 2d and topdown maps, and npc x y z scale path category subtype on 3d maps.
The fields are space separated, where x, y, and (on 3d maps) z are the tile coordinates the creature spawns at, scale is an integer scale level, path is one of any, global, or map, and category and subtype name the folder under sounds/<pack>/builder/kombat/npc/.

The path value decides where the creature reads its info.sif from. Any uses the map's local copy if it exists and falls back to the global pack otherwise. Global pins the lookup to sounds/<pack>/builder/kombat/npc/ even if a map local copy is present. Map pins it to data/builder/maps/decompiled/<map>/assets/builder/kombat/npc/ and refuses the global fallback. This lets two creatures of the same name on the same map intentionally read different stats by pointing at different paths.
A subtype of none places nothing and is silently ignored at parse time, which is useful as a placeholder when blocking out a map.

The line is read back on map load and the creature placed automatically, so editing this file by hand is a valid way to bulk place creatures without going through the builder.

Scale level.

The scale value on a spawn line decides whether the creature uses its hand authored stats or auto scales to the player.

A scale level of zero spawns the creature with the exact health, attack, ranges, and every other stat the info.sif file provides, which is the right choice for hand placed peaceful villagers, tutorial creatures, or set piece encounters where you want exact control.
A scale level of one or higher overrides those stats with auto generated values: attack ranges collapse to zero, sight ranges expand to the full map, max health and attack are derived from the player's current xp, lives drop to one, fire and move timers are randomized between one hundred and one thousand milliseconds, the level field is set to the chosen scale value, the xp drop equals the level, and movement and item drops are randomized booleans.

Any scale level above zero scales the spawned creature to threaten the player at their current progression, which is what bosses and spawn zones use under the hood.

The wounded and healing variant stats are also blanked out under scale, so an auto scaled creature has no flee or healing behavior even if the underlying info.sif configures one.

NPC zones.

NPC zones are the auto respawn variant of a single spawn line.
Instead of placing one creature once, a zone defines an x range and a y coordinate (plus a z coordinate on 3d maps) that, when the player walks across it, spawns a creature on a timer.

Zones live in the map info.sif as npc_zone minx maxx y spawntime scale path category subtype on 2d and topdown maps, and npc_zone minx maxx y z spawntime scale path category subtype on 3d maps. They are written by the npc zone builder under zones.
Walking onto any tile in the zone's minx to maxx range at the matching y starts the spawn timer, and once spawntime milliseconds have elapsed a creature is spawned at a random x inside the range, the timer restarts, and the next spawn is queued.

Setting subtype to random rolls a random folder from the chosen category on every spawn, so a single zone can spit out a different creature each time it fires.

The scale field works the same as on spawn lines: zero uses static info.sif stats, one or higher auto scales to the player. The path field works the same way too, with any, global, and map deciding which info.sif copy each spawned creature reads from.
Combined with random subtype and a high scale, a zone becomes an open ended encounter generator that keeps producing fresh threats as long as you stand in it.
